"""
MKT Original Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 18–19 (fill)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-2kings-18-19-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/2kings.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/2kings.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch18: Hezekiah narrative saturated with bāṭaḥ (trust) root — tracked through Rabshakeh's rhetorical assault
- Nehushtan (v4): nēḥûštān pun on nāḥāš (serpent) + nᵉḥōšet (bronze) — treated as Hezekiah's deliberate
  desacralization naming, stripping the object of numinous power
- Rabshakeh's claim of YHWH's commission (18:25) noted as either propaganda or a garbled reference to
  Isaiah's earlier oracles against Judah; treated as rhetorical weaponization of YHWH's name
- Silence of the people (18:36): dāmam root — commanded as royal discipline but also narratively
  represents trust against the Rabshakeh's invitation to panic
- Ch19: Hezekiah's prayer structure follows standard Hebrew lament form; qinʾat YHWH ṣᵉḇāʾôt (v31)
  treated as divine passion/jealousy driving restoration
- "Angel of the LORD" (19:35): malʾak YHWH as divine warrior; 185,000 figure consistent with Assyrian
  annalistic boasting being silenced by catastrophic defeat
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "18": {
    "1": '<p>The synchronistic date formula — "In the third year of Hoshea … Hezekiah became king" — links the two kingdoms chronologically in the manner of the Assyrian limmu lists. It places Hezekiah\'s reign in direct relationship with Hoshea\'s final years, making the contrast between faithful Judah and about-to-fall Israel a structural feature of the narrative.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The queen-mother formula ("his mother\'s name was…") appears in almost every Judahite accession notice and is absent from Northern kingdom notices. The queen mother held a formal court position (<em>gᵉbîrāh</em>); her name\'s preservation signals dynastic legitimacy. "Abi" is a theophoric short form — "my father [is YHWH]."</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>hayyāšār bᵉʿênê YHWH</strong> — the royal assessment formula appears in nearly every Judahite regnal notice. "Just as his ancestor David had done" (kᵉdāwid ʾāḇîw) is the highest possible rating; only Josiah receives comparable language. The Davidic standard is not merely moral but covenantal — it invokes YHWH\'s promises to David as the framework for evaluating each king.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>Nehushtan</strong> (<em>nēḥûštān</em>, v4b): the bronze serpent Moses made in Num 21:8–9 had become an object of incense offerings. Hezekiah breaks it and assigns it the contemptuous name <em>nēḥûštān</em> — a wordplay on <em>nāḥāš</em> (serpent, H5175) and <em>nᵉḥōšet</em> (bronze, H5178), reducing it to "a mere piece of bronze." The naming is an act of desacralization: by exposing the object\'s material nature, Hezekiah strips it of numinous power. That the reformer must destroy what Moses made is itself theologically loaded — a cultic object with a legitimate origin can still become an idol.</p><p>The broader reform (demolishing high places, smashing sacred pillars, cutting Asherah poles) parallels the Deuteronomic program; Hezekiah is the first king credited with actually carrying it out.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>dāḇaq</strong> (H1692, "clung") — the covenant loyalty verb. Deut 10:20 commands Israel to "cling to" (<em>tiḏbāq</em>) YHWH; Deut 30:20 pairs it with "love" and "obey." The narrator applies this verb to Hezekiah personally — he is the Deuteronomic ideal king before Josiah. "Did not depart from following him" uses the idiom <em>sûr mēʾaḥărāyw</em> — literally "turn aside from behind him" — the language of a servant who never abandons his lord\'s path.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>hāyāh ʿimmô YHWH</strong> — "YHWH was with him" is the narrator\'s theological verdict on military success; the same formula appears for David (1 Sam 18:14). "He succeeded in everything he undertook" (<em>bᵉkōl ʾăšer yēṣēʾ yaśkîl</em>) echoes the Josh 1:7–8 promise — prosperity as the result of Torah fidelity. The rebellion against Assyria is presented as an act of faith consistent with this trust.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"From watchtower to fortified city" (<em>miggiddal nôṣᵉrîm ʿad-ʿîr miḇṣār</em>) is a merism for the full territory — every settlement from smallest garrison outpost to largest walled city. The Philistine campaign is historically corroborated by Assyrian records noting Judean expansion into Philistia in this period.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The doubled synchronism — "the fourth year of Hezekiah, the seventh year of Hoshea" — is deliberate historiographic framing. The narrator is setting up a theological contrast: as Samaria is falling (ch17), Hezekiah is trusting. The date anchor ties the two stories together so the reader cannot miss the comparison.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"After three years they captured it" — the three-year siege (724–722 BC) ended in Samaria\'s fall. The narrator states this matter-of-factly from Hezekiah\'s chronological reference point ("the sixth year of Hezekiah, the ninth year of Hoshea"). The passive construction ("Samaria was captured") avoids naming Sargon II; YHWH is the implied agent, as v12 will make explicit.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The deportation geography — Halah, Habor, Gozan, cities of the Medes — represents the Assyrian practice of mass relocation to break ethnic cohesion and prevent rebellion. These are actual places in the Assyrian heartland and periphery, verifiable from cuneiform records.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The theological explanation — "because they did not listen (<em>lōʾ šāmᵉʿû</em>) to the voice of the LORD" — uses the <em>šāmaʿ</em> (hear/obey) root that is programmatic in Deuteronomy. "Violated his covenant" (<em>ʿāḇrû ʾet-bᵉrîtô</em>) and "everything Moses the servant of the LORD commanded" — the Deuteronomic covenant as the legal standard by which Israel was judged. This summary is the narrator\'s homily; it makes the deportation a theological rather than merely political event.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>ʿālāh</strong> — "came up against" (H5927) — the standard verb for military invasion. The year is Hezekiah\'s 14th (ca. 701 BC), corresponding to Sennacherib\'s third campaign, documented in his annals at the Oriental Institute. The "fortified cities of Judah" (ʿārê-yᵉhûdāh habᵉṣûrôt) — Assyrian sources list 46 Judahite cities captured, consistent with the narrative.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>ḥāṭāʾtî</strong> — "I have sinned" is the language of admission before a superior. Hezekiah submits and asks for a tribute assessment. "Whatever you impose on me I will bear" (<em>ʾēt ʾăšer-tittēn ʿālay ʾeśśāʾ</em>) — the root <em>nāśāʾ</em> (to bear, carry) signals complete capitulation. This episode of tribute payment is not contradicted by the later deliverance; it represents an earlier, distinct engagement before Sennacherib pushed further.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The silver total — three hundred talents — matches the figure in Sennacherib\'s own annals, a rare textual correspondence between a biblical narrative and external Assyrian records. This unusual agreement gives the tribute payment historical grounding.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Hezekiah strips the gold he himself had plated on the temple doors and posts — the irony is pointed: the king who was praised for purifying and maintaining the temple now must despoil it under military duress. The verb <em>qiṣṣēṣ</em> ("stripped off, cut off") is sharp and denudes the temple of its royal adornment.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Three Assyrian titles arrive: <strong>Tartan</strong> (<em>tartān</em>) = commander-in-chief (Akkadian <em>turtānu</em>); <strong>Rab-saris</strong> = chief eunuch or court official (<em>rabša-rēši</em>); <strong>Rabshakeh</strong> (<em>rabšāqēh</em>) = chief officer, probably a political/propaganda envoy (Akkadian <em>rabi-šāqê</em>). The three together represent a full Assyrian delegation of military, administrative, and diplomatic weight. They arrive with "a large army" (<em>ḥayil kāḇēd</em>). The Upper Pool aqueduct and the Fuller\'s Field — the same location where Isaiah confronted Ahaz in Isa 7:3 — gives the confrontation an intertextual resonance.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Three Judahite officials face the delegation: <strong>Eliakim</strong> son of Hilkiah (palace administrator, <em>ʾăšer ʿal-habbayit</em>); <strong>Shebna</strong> the secretary (<em>sōpēr</em>); <strong>Joah</strong> the recorder (<em>mazzᵉkîr</em>). Isaiah 22:15–25 specifically condemned Shebna and predicted his removal — he appears here in a demoted role (secretary rather than palace administrator), suggesting the prophecy was partially fulfilled already.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The Rabshakeh opens with a pointed rhetorical question deploying the <em>bāṭaḥ</em> (trust) root: <strong>mah-habbittāḥôn hazzeh ʾăšer bāṭāḥtā</strong> — "What is this confidence in which you have trusted?" He uses the noun <em>bittāḥôn</em> (H986) and the verb <em>bāṭaḥ</em> (H982) in a single phrase, weaponizing the vocabulary of Hezekiah\'s piety (v5) against him. The entire speech is built around this term: trust in military strategy? trust in Egypt? trust in YHWH? Each is attacked in turn.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>qāneh rāṣûṣ</strong> — "a crushed/broken reed" (H7070 + H7533) — Egypt as a staff that splinters and pierces the hand of anyone who leans on it. The image is vivid and tactile: the very support becomes the wound. The phrase appears also in Isa 36:6 and Ezek 29:6–7. The Rabshakeh\'s Egypt critique is politically accurate — Egypt\'s military power was often promised and rarely delivered; Pharaoh as "Rahab who sits still" in Isa 30:7 makes the same point.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The "wager" (H6148, <em>hāʿeḇ-nāʾ</em> — "make a pledge/stake") of two thousand horses if Hezekiah can provide riders: a crushing rhetorical point. Judah cannot field cavalry to match even this hypothetical offer. The Assyrian cavalry and chariotry were the world\'s most advanced; Judah\'s military weakness in that arena is historical fact. The argument is designed to expose the gap between trust and military reality.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"How can you repel one captain of the least of my master\'s servants?" — <em>pānim ʾeḥāḏ pᵉḥat ʾaḥad ʿăḇāḏê ʾăḏōnî haqqᵉṭannîm</em> — "the face of one officer among the least servants of my lord." The rhetorical escalation: not even a low-ranking Assyrian officer could Judah repel. "Egypt for chariots and horsemen" — the dependence on Egyptian military aid is exposed as inadequate before the scale of Assyrian power.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The Rabshakeh\'s boldest claim: "Did I come up against this place without the LORD? The LORD said to me, Go up against this land and destroy it." This is either deliberate propaganda (the Assyrians knew YHWH\'s name from Israelite deportees) or a garbled reference to YHWH\'s actual judgment oracles against Judah (Isa 10:5–6 calls Assyria "the rod of YHWH\'s anger"). The rhetorical effect is to make resistance seem not merely futile but actively impious — as if YHWH himself commissioned the attack.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>ʾărāmît</strong> — Aramaic was the diplomatic and trade language of the ancient Near East by the 8th century BC — the <em>lingua franca</em> of the Assyrian imperial correspondence. Hebrew (<em>yᵉhûdît</em>) was the Judahite vernacular. The officials\' request to use Aramaic is a request to conduct the negotiation in the channel of power without exposing the content to the people. The Rabshakeh\'s refusal is calculated: psychological warfare requires that the population hear the terms directly.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The graphic imagery — "eat their own dung and drink their own urine" — is the language of siege conditions. The Rabshakeh is invoking the horror of prolonged siege: starvation so severe that the people would consume waste. The Akkadian cognates suggest this was standard imperial intimidation language. His point: the people, not just the king, bear the cost of resistance, and they should know it.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>qōl gādōl</strong> — "a loud voice" — the public proclamation form. The Rabshakeh abandons diplomatic protocol and addresses the people directly over the heads of their officials. "Listen to the words of the great king, the king of Assyria" — the titulary <em>melek rāḇ</em> (great king) is an Assyrian self-designation (<em>šarru rabû</em>) claiming universal sovereignty. The public address is an act of psychological siege before the military siege.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The first of four negative commands: "Do not let Hezekiah deceive you" — <em>yašśîʾ ʾetkem</em>, the hiphil of <em>nāšāʾ</em> (to deceive, H5377). The argument is that trust in Hezekiah\'s ability to deliver is misplaced. "He cannot rescue you from my power" — <em>lōʾ yûkal lᵉhaṣṣîl ʾetkem miyyāḏô</em> — contrasting Hezekiah\'s claimed rescue with the Rabshakeh\'s certainty of Assyrian power.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"Do not let Hezekiah persuade you to trust in the LORD" — <em>yabṭaḥ ʾetkem ʾel-YHWH</em>. The second attack uses the <em>bāṭaḥ</em> root again — now applied to YHWH as the object of trust. "The LORD will certainly rescue us; this city will not be given into the hand of the king of Assyria" — he quotes what YHWH\'s claim would be, then proceeds to undermine it. The speech attempts to separate the people from their theological confidence.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Make peace with me and surrender" — <em>ʿăśû-ittî bᵉrākāh</em> — literally "make a blessing with me"; a euphemism for capitulation and tribute. What follows is the classic Assyrian peace offer: "every one from his own vine and from his own fig tree" — a deliberate echo of the prosperity language of the Davidic covenant (1 Kgs 4:25; Mic 4:4). The Rabshakeh is promising Hezekiah\'s covenant blessings under Assyrian patronage — a theological parody.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"A land like your own" (<em>ʾereṣ kᵉʾarṣᵉkem</em>) — the land-promise of the Deuteronomic blessing is offered under Assyrian terms: grain, wine, bread, vineyards, olive trees, honey. The vocabulary of the promised land is co-opted to describe Mesopotamian resettlement. The offer is designed to make deportation seem like a viable alternative to siege, mimicking the Deuteronomic promise structure while severing it from its covenantal ground.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The comparative theology argument: "Has any god of the nations ever rescued his land from the king of Assyria?" The rhetorical question surveys the record of defeat — Hamath, Arpad, Sepharvaim. From an empirical standpoint, the answer is clearly no; no national deity has stood against Assyria. The argument is inductive: YHWH is being treated as one national deity among many, and the induction favors Assyrian victory.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The defeated gods of Hamath, Arpad, Sepharvaim, Hena, Ivvah are presented as a catalog of failures. The names are authentic North Syrian and Mesopotamian cities and their associated deities. The Rabshakeh\'s argument would be unassailable if YHWH were simply another territorial deity — the narrative answer (ch19) is that YHWH is not.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"Which of all the gods of these lands has rescued his territory from me?" — the universalizing claim. Every conquered nation had its gods; all gods failed. "How then will the LORD rescue Jerusalem from my hand?" — the argument reaches its logical conclusion. The speech is rhetorically coherent within its own theological framework; it fails only when YHWH turns out not to be that kind of god.</p>',
    "36": '<p><strong>wayyihdᵉmû hāʿām</strong> — "the people were silent" — from the root <em>dāmam</em> (H1826), to be still, silent, motionless. The king had commanded, "Do not answer him" (<em>lōʾ taʿănuhû dāḇār</em>). The silence is both royal discipline and a narrative moment of trust: the people do not capitulate verbally to the Rabshakeh\'s invitation to panic. Their silence is the text\'s implied counter to the speech.</p>',
    "37": '<p>The three officials report to Hezekiah with torn clothes (<em>qᵉrûʿê bᵉgāḏîm</em>) — a sign of grief and distress. The report comes as a formal state communication; the officials act as the transmission point between the external threat and the king\'s response, which begins ch19.</p>'
  },
  "19": {
    "1": '<p>Hezekiah\'s immediate response is the full penitential form: tearing clothes (<em>wayyiqraʿ ʾet-bᵉgāḏāyw</em>) + sackcloth (<em>wayyitkaś baśśāq</em>) + going to the temple. The sequence parallels David\'s and Josiah\'s responses to crisis. Going to the temple is not merely religious observance — it is a physical act of bringing the crisis into YHWH\'s presence, placing it before the one who alone can resolve it.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Hezekiah sends to Isaiah — "the prophet, the son of Amoz" — the full designation signals formal prophetic consultation. The delegation includes Eliakim, Shebna, and the senior priests, all in sackcloth — the court models the royal penitential posture. Isaiah functions here in his role as court prophet, the institutional mediator between royal crisis and divine response.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"A day of distress, rebuke, and disgrace" — <em>ṣārāh wᵉtôkāḥat ûnᵉʾāṣāh</em> — three nouns of acute crisis. The "children come to the opening of the womb, but there is no strength to give birth" — <em>bānîm bāʾû ʿad-mōṣāʾ wᵉḵōaḥ ʾayin lᵉlēdāh</em>. The birth metaphor for crisis is used elsewhere in the psalms (Ps 48:6) and prophets (Isa 37:3). The image is of labor that reaches the moment of crisis but cannot complete — maximum vulnerability with no ability to deliver.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>ʾĕlōhîm ḥayyîm</strong> — "the living God" — this is the theological counter to the Rabshakeh\'s catalog of dead national deities (18:33–35). By naming YHWH as "living," Hezekiah\'s message to Isaiah frames the crisis as a category error on the Rabshakeh\'s part: he has compared YHWH to gods who cannot speak, act, or hear. "Perhaps YHWH your God will hear" — the <em>ʾûlay</em> (perhaps) is not uncertainty about YHWH\'s power but the proper humility of a petitioner.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A brief transitional verse — the servants\' arrival at Isaiah. The narrator\'s economy here contrasts with the speech elaboration of ch18; the prophetic response will be correspondingly immediate. No extended negotiation is needed because Isaiah already has a word from YHWH.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Isaiah\'s oracle of salvation (<em>ôrākle de salut</em>) opens with the standard formula <em>ʾal-tîrāʾ</em> — "do not be afraid" — the reassurance formula that marks prophetic oracles of divine intervention throughout Isaiah (Isa 7:4; 10:24; 37:6; 41:10). "The words you have heard" (<em>haddᵉḇārîm ʾăšer šāmaʿtā</em>) — YHWH validates that he has heard the Rabshakeh\'s speech; the words against the holy one have reached YHWH\'s ears.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"I am going to put a spirit in him" — <em>nōtēn bô rûaḥ</em> — YHWH acts directly on Sennacherib\'s perception. <em>Rûaḥ</em> (H7307) here is a psychological/perceptual agent — a disposition, report, or impulse that will redirect him. "He will hear a report" (<em>wᵉšāmaʿ šᵉmûʿāh</em>) — <em>šᵉmûʿāh</em> (H8052) is "news, tidings" — the Tirhakah report (v9) is the fulfillment. "Fall by the sword in his own land" — the warrior boaster dies not in siege but in his own temple (v37), killed by his own sons.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The Rabshakeh returns to find Sennacherib fighting at Libnah — the narrative gap explains why Sennacherib could not advance on Jerusalem immediately. Lachish is now taken; the campaign shifts. The transitional verses (8–9) show Sennacherib still active in Judah while the divine response is being prepared.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Tirhakah king of Ethiopia (Cush) — historically Taharqa, who became Pharaoh in 690 BC but was involved in anti-Assyrian coalition politics earlier. The news of his approach gives Sennacherib reason to intensify his Jerusalem diplomatic pressure. "He sent messengers again to Hezekiah" — the second letter follows the same pattern as the speech but in writing (v14).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The second Assyrian message deploys the same theological argument: "Do not let your God, in whom you are trusting, deceive you" — <em>ʾal-yašśiʾkā ʾĕlōhêkā ʾăšer-ʾattāh bōṭēaḥ bô</em>. <em>Bāṭaḥ</em> appears again — the Assyrian diplomacy consistently targets Hezekiah\'s trust as the vulnerability. The argument: Jerusalem\'s deliverance is a deception YHWH is perpetrating on Hezekiah, not a promise he can keep.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"You have heard what the kings of Assyria have done to all the countries" — the empirical survey returns. <em>ḥᵉrēm</em> (H2763) is used — "utterly destroying them" — the devotion-to-destruction term. The letter rehearses the same inductive argument: every nation destroyed, you will be no different. The shift from speech to letter is significant; it gives the argument a more formal, documented character.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The catalog of defeated nations and their gods: Gozan (on the Habor River in Assyria), Haran (ancestral Abrahamic site), Rezeph (on the Euphrates), Eden (Beth-Eden, an Aramean kingdom). "The gods of those nations did not deliver them" — the premise is identical to 18:33–35. The Assyrian archive of conquest is offered as the decisive proof against YHWH\'s ability to intervene.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A rhetorical question — "Where are the kings of Hamath, Arpad, Sepharvaim, Hena, and Ivvah?" — answers itself: they are gone, deposed, their cities destroyed. The past tense of defeat is the tense of certainty about Jerusalem\'s future, in Sennacherib\'s logic. The cities listed span from Northern Syria to the Euphrates, representing the full sweep of Assyrian conquest.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Hezekiah "received the letter" (<em>wayyiqqaḥ … ʾet-hassᵉpārîm</em>) and "spread it out before the LORD" (<em>wayyipprᵉśēhû liphᵉnê YHWH</em>). The physical act of laying the threatening letter before YHWH in the temple is remarkable — it is the anti-prayer version of bringing complaints to the judge. Hezekiah presents the written threat as evidence, letting YHWH see what has been said. This is prayer through enacted metaphor: the one who reads all things is asked to read the enemy\'s letter.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The prayer\'s opening invocation — "O LORD, God of Israel, enthroned between the cherubim" (<em>YHWH ʾĕlōhê yiśrāʾēl yōšēḇ hakkᵉrûḇîm</em>) — uses the throne-room epithet also in Ps 80:1; 99:1; 1 Sam 4:4. The cherubim are the ark\'s guardians; this is YHWH as present in his earthly throne room in the temple, not an absent deity. "You alone are God over all the kingdoms of the earth" (<em>ʾattāh-hûʾ hāʾĕlōhîm lᵉḇaḏᵉkā lᵉkōl mamlᵉkôt hāʾāreṣ</em>) — the universal sovereignty claim directly counters the Rabshakeh\'s "which of the gods of the nations." YHWH is not one among them.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Incline your ear, LORD, and hear; open your eyes, LORD, and see" — the anthropomorphic petition uses the physical senses of hearing and sight to invoke divine attentiveness. The double address (<em>YHWH … YHWH</em>) and the two imperatives (<em>haṭṭēh … pᵉqaḥ</em>) are the lament form\'s call for divine action. "Words Sennacherib has sent to mock the living God" (<em>ḥērap ʾet-ʾĕlōhîm ḥay</em>) — returns the <em>ḥayyîm</em> (living) epithet from v4, making mockery of the living God the central charge against Sennacherib.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Hezekiah concedes the historical fact: "It is true, LORD, that the kings of Assyria have destroyed these nations and their lands." The concession is rhetorically significant — Hezekiah\'s prayer is honest. He does not deny the evidence; he reframes its meaning. The Assyrian conquests were real, but the explanation for them is theological, not testimonial of YHWH\'s weakness.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"They have thrown their gods into the fire — for those were no gods at all, merely human handiwork, wood and stone" (<em>lōʾ ʾĕlōhîm hēmmāh kî ʾim-maʿăśēh yᵉḏê-ʾāḏām ʿēṣ wāʾeḇen wayyᵃʾaḇᵉḏûm</em>). The theological axiom: the defeated "gods" were no gods — they were human artifacts that could be burned. The destruction of national deities by Assyria proves only that idols cannot survive fire, not that YHWH cannot survive Sennacherib. The argument dismantles the Rabshakeh\'s induction by distinguishing categories of deity.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"Now, O LORD our God, deliver us from his hand" — the petition follows the theological argument: having established that YHWH is categorically different from the national deities, Hezekiah asks for the act that will demonstrate it. "So that all the kingdoms of the earth may know that you, LORD, are God alone" (<em>lᵉmaʿan yēḏᵉʿû kōl mamlᵉkôt hāʾāreṣ kî ʾattāh YHWH ʾĕlōhîm lᵉḇaḏᵉkā</em>) — the witness formula. Deliverance is not merely self-preservation; it is testimony. The nations need to know what YHWH is, and only an act of deliverance can demonstrate it.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Isaiah\'s response — "I have heard your prayer" (<em>šāmaʿtî</em>) — uses the same <em>šāmaʿ</em> root that the Rabshakeh used to taunt ("did I come up without the LORD saying…?"). YHWH has heard, in contrast to the gods who could not hear (18:34–35). The messenger formula — "This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says" — frames what follows as divine speech, not Isaiah\'s editorial comment.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"The virgin daughter of Zion despises and mocks you; the daughter of Jerusalem wags her head behind you" — <em>bᵉtûlat bat-ṣiyyôn</em> is the feminine personification of Jerusalem as YHWH\'s city. The mocking gesture — wagging the head (<em>nāʿăh rōʾš</em>) — is an inversion of the Rabshakeh\'s own mockery (18:27). Jerusalem is not the terrified city Sennacherib imagines; she laughs at him. The oracle opens with contempt before moving to judgment.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Through your messengers you have taunted the Lord" — <em>bᵉyaḏ malʾākêkā ḥēraptā ʾăḏōnāy</em> — the charge is not against Hezekiah but directly against Sennacherib\'s own speech. "With my many chariots I climbed to the top of the mountains" — the boast of Assyrian military engineering. "I will cut down its tallest cedars" — the Lebanon cedar was the symbol of imperial reach and pride. The imagery is inverted: the one who boasts of conquest is addressed as the object of YHWH\'s judgment.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"I dug wells and drank foreign water; with the soles of my feet I dried up all the streams of Egypt" — the hyperbolic self-praise of the Assyrian conqueror, who claims even to have altered the hydrology of Egypt. The image of drying the Nile\'s branches with footsteps is military boasting in its most grandiose form. YHWH\'s oracle quotes these words back, implicitly to expose their absurdity.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Have you not heard? I determined this long ago; from ancient times I planned it" — the divine sovereignty claim that Sennacherib\'s conquests were YHWH\'s prior plan, not Sennacherib\'s achievement. <em>mêrāḥôq yāṣartîhā</em> — "from afar I formed it" — the verb <em>yāṣar</em> (H3335, to form, shape as a potter) is the same verb used of God forming humanity (Gen 2:7). Sennacherib\'s victories were YHWH\'s pottery, not Sennacherib\'s conquest. The great empires are instruments of divine purpose, not autonomous powers.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"That is why their inhabitants had so little power — they were shattered and ashamed" — the passive victims of Assyrian conquest were so only because YHWH had predestined it. <em>ḥattû wāḇōšû</em> — shattered and ashamed — the vocabulary of defeat in its full humiliation. The "plants of the field … grass on the rooftops" simile (<em>kᵉḏešeʾ śādeh ûkᵉyereq deśeʾ ḥāṣîr gaggôt</em>) — the conquests as grass that sprouts and withers quickly, rootless and ephemeral before YHWH\'s plans.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"But I know where you live and when you come and go, and I know your rage against me" (<em>wᵉyōšbᵉkā wᵉṣēʾtkā ûbōʾekā yāḏaʿtî</em>). YHWH\'s omniscience over Sennacherib is total: his residence, his movements, his inner rage (<em>rigzô</em>). The contrast with the Rabshakeh\'s taunt — "the LORD said to me, Go up" — is complete: it was not Sennacherib directing YHWH but YHWH directing Sennacherib, and now YHWH knows all of it including the boast.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Because your fury against me and your arrogance have reached my ears, I will put my hook in your nose and my bridle in your mouth" — <em>wᵉśamtî ḥaḥî bᵉʾappekā ûmitgî bᵉśᵉpātêkā</em>. The hook-in-nose and bridle imagery is precisely what Assyria did to conquered peoples; Assyrian palace reliefs show captive kings led with hooks through their lips. YHWH turns Sennacherib\'s own imperial apparatus on him — the instruments of domination become the instruments of his humiliation. "I will make you go back the same way you came" — the retreat is YHWH\'s direction, not Sennacherib\'s choice.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The sign for Hezekiah is agricultural: this year (<em>hašššānāh</em>) eat what grows on its own (<em>sāpîaḥ</em>), second year what springs from that (<em>šāḵîš</em>), third year plant and harvest (<em>zirʿû wiqṣōrû</em>). The three-year timeline is precise. The sign is not dramatic but patient: the land\'s agricultural restoration over time, showing that YHWH\'s deliverance is not a one-time miracle but a new normal of security. "Growing on its own" presupposes disruption of normal agriculture — the siege year had prevented planting.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"The surviving remnant of the house of Judah will again take root downward and bear fruit upward" — <em>wᵉhōsîpāh pᵉlêṭat bêt-yᵉhûdāh hannišʾāret šōreš lᵉmattāh wᵉʿāśāh pᵉrî lᵉmaʿlāh</em>. The <em>remnant</em> (<em>pᵉlêṭāh</em>) motif is Isaianic — a theological category that runs through the book. "Take root downward" is the image of organic stability; "bear fruit upward" is the image of flourishing. The reversal from crisis to fruitfulness is described in botanical terms, quietly but profoundly.</p>',
    "31": '<p><strong>qinʾat YHWH ṣᵉḇāʾôt</strong> — "the zeal of the LORD of hosts" (H7068) will accomplish this. <em>Qinʾāh</em> is divine passion/jealousy — the same burning drive that YHWH has for exclusive covenant relationship and for his own honor. It is not sentiment but energy; it is what moves YHWH to act on behalf of his remnant against the empire. "The LORD of hosts" (<em>YHWH ṣᵉḇāʾôt</em>) — the title of YHWH as commander of the heavenly armies, especially relevant when military power is the visible threat.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The fourfold guarantee against Sennacherib entering Jerusalem: will not enter this city / will not shoot an arrow here / will not come before it with a shield / will not pour a siege ramp against it. Each element represents a standard Assyrian siege tactic. The list is technically precise — the four methods are exactly what siege armies would use. YHWH\'s prohibition is equally precise: none of these tactics will be employed against Jerusalem.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"He will go back the same way he came" — the reversal formula. YHWH\'s declaration reverses the direction of the invasion. <em>ûbaḏderek ʾăšer-bāʾ bāh yāšûḇ</em> — the exact path of ingress becomes the path of retreat. The Deuteronomic blessing and curse structures have a similar reversal pattern; blessing and cursing are directional. "Declares the LORD" (<em>nᵉʾum-YHWH</em>) — the prophetic speech-act formula sealing the oracle.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"I will defend this city and save it, for my own sake and for the sake of my servant David" — the dual motivation is theologically significant. <em>lᵉmaʿănî</em> (for my own sake) — YHWH\'s honor is at stake; the Rabshakeh\'s taunt against YHWH is answered by YHWH\'s action. <em>ûlᵉmaʿan dāwid ʿaḇdî</em> (for the sake of my servant David) — the Davidic covenant is the other ground; Jerusalem\'s protection is a covenant obligation, not merely a display of power. These two motivations together span divine honor and covenant faithfulness.</p>',
    "35": '<p><strong>malʾak YHWH</strong> — the angel of the LORD as divine warrior. "That night" (<em>wayᵉhî ballaylāh hahûʾ</em>) — the night setting for divine intervention is consistent with the Passover and Exodus typology. "A hundred and eighty-five thousand men in the Assyrian camp" — <em>mēʾāh šᵉmōnîm wᵉḥāmêšāh ʾelep</em>. The number is large and has been debated; Assyrian annals often overcount victories. Whatever the historical event, the narrative is clear: the morning reveals mass death without battle (<em>kullām pᵉḡārîm mētîm</em> — "they were all dead bodies"). The divine warrior wins without Judahite military action — YHWH alone defends Jerusalem.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Sennacherib "broke camp and withdrew and returned to Nineveh, where he stayed" — the six verbs of departure (<em>wayyisaʿ wayyēlek wayyāšob</em> etc.) narrate his exit with blunt economy. The boaster of 18:33–35 simply goes home. The contrast between the elaborate rhetorical assault and the bare narrative of retreat is the text\'s understated triumph. His annals, by contrast, claim a great victory — the propagandistic gap is historically instructive.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Sennacherib is killed by his own sons Adrammelech and Sharezer while "worshipping in the house of Nisroch his god" (<em>bêt nisrōk ʾĕlōhāyw</em>). The irony is complete: the man who mocked YHWH by comparing him to powerless national deities (18:33–35) dies in the temple of one of those deities, at the hands of his own sons. "Nisroch" is not securely identified; possibly a form of Nusku or Marduk. "They escaped to the land of Ararat" — Urartu (modern Armenia) — corroborated in Assyrian and Babylonian records. Esarhaddon reigned in his place — the dynasty continues, but Sennacherib himself falls by the sword in his own land, exactly as YHWH predicted (v7).</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', '2kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-original', '2kings', existing)
    for ch in ['18', '19']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
